<!-- SC_OFF --><div class="md"><p>I&#39;ve wondering whether it&#39;s possible, and wise to redirect the output of pacman to a logfile or /dev/null. I want to create a script that send the least amount of information to the Screen, however, I&#39;d like the information to be useful as well.</p> <p>I also want to avoid removing pacman prompts from the user&#39;s view.</p> <p>Is there a pacman option for a quieter less verbose mode? or could I do something like</p> <p><code>sudo pacman -Syu 2&gt;&amp;1 SomeLogFile.txt</code></p> <p>Why might that be a good or bad idea? Are there better alternatives?</p> <p>Thanks.</p> <p>EDIT:</p> <p>Thanks to <a href="/u/lucasrizzini">u/lucasrizzini</a> for providing some sane pacman and terminal commands for dealing with pacman&#39;s output. This is looking quite promising for a script usage.</p> </div><!-- SC_ON --> &#32; submitted by &#32; <a href="https://www.reddit.com/user/RandomXUsr"> /u/RandomXUsr </a> <br/> <span><a href="https://www.reddit.com/r/archlinux/comments/w1hhwq/pacman_stdout_and_stderr_redirection_via_script/">[link]</a></span> &#32; <span><a href="https://www.reddit.com/r/archlinux/comments/w1hhwq/pacman_stdout_and_stderr_redirection_via_script/">[comments]</a></span>